generif.text: This report describes the first cloning and characterization of a novel CATERPILLER gene, CLR16.2 that is located on human chromosome 16. The protein encoded by this gene has a typical NBD-LRR configuration.
Post-transcriptional inhibition of luciferase reporter assays by the Nod-like receptor proteins NLRX1 and NLRC3.
NLRC3 inhibited Toll-like receptor (TLR)-dependent activation of the transcription factor NF-kappaB by interacting with the TLR signaling adaptor TRAF6
overexpression of NLRC3 with NLRP3/cryopyrin inflammasome components suppresses pro-caspase-1 cleavage and IL-1beta processing.
The extent of NLRC3 and AIM2 gene reduction was correlated with cancer progression.
NLRX1, NLRP12 and NLRC3 negatively modulate the host immune response following virus exposure. (Review)
The NLRC3 interferes with the assembly and activity of the NALP3 inflammasome complex by competing with ASC for pro-caspase-1 binding.
NLRC3 promoted K48-linked polyubiquitination and degradation of interleukin-1 receptor-associated kinase 1 (IRAK1).
Down-regulated expression of NLRC3 may play an important role in cancer progression and prognosis of HCC by acting as a tumor suppressor.
expression of NLRC3 was significantly associated with CD8+ T cells infiltration
NLRC3 silencing accelerates the invasion of hepatocellular carcinoma cell via IL-6/JAK2/STAT3 pathway activation.
[Knockdown of NLRC3 promotes proliferation and invasion of human colon cancer cells].
NLRC3 is a potential prognostic biomarker that is correlated with immune cell infiltration in lung adenocarcinoma.
NLRC3 deficiency promotes hypoxia-induced pulmonary hypertension development via IKK/NF-kappaB p65/HIF-1alpha pathway.
Decoding the IBD paradox: A triadic interplay between REG3, enterococci, and NOD2.

reactome.name: STING mediated induction of host immune responses
IRF3-mediated induction of type I IFN

summary: This gene encodes a NOD-like receptor family member. The encoded protein is a cytosolic regulator of innate immunity. This protein directly interacts with stimulator of interferon genes (STING), to prevent its proper trafficking, resulting in disruption of STING-dependent activation of the innate immune response. Alternative splicing results in multiple transcript variants. [provided by RefSeq, Feb 2014].
